ce:section.ce:para:
Biophysical (average cell height, RMS roughness, cell spreading area) and biomechanical (cell stiffness; Young’s modulus) properties can influence the natural properties of cells. These biophysical and biomechanical properties are known as the defining factors in the differentiation of stem cells. Several studies reported the relationship between the cellular response and the differentiation of stem cells, and these studies deployed Bio-AFM to examine the inter-related response [23,39–41]. In this study, the cells were first treated with Glu-GQDs and Gr-GQDs (512 μg/mL) for 24 h; subsequently, the Bio-AFM utilized to cell morphology images (100 μm × 100 μm, 40 μm × 40 μm, and 10 μm × 10 μm) and measure the change in the biophysical and biomechanical properties. In the morphological study, filopodia, lamellipodia, and invadopodia were observed in all the groups, and the overall shape of the cells did not change except for the cell surface. The changes on the cell surface were evident after treatment with the two types of GQDs. In the case of NHDF, compared to the control group, the cell surface became much rougher when the cells were treated with Glu-GQDs and Gr-GQDs (Fig. 5
                        (B) and (C)). In addition, the pore and bleb, which indicate cell apoptosis, were found to be larger size upon cell treatment with Glu-GQDs and Gr-GQDs, as compared to the control group. In case of HeLa, no specific change in cell shape was not observed, but the blebs on the surface were more prominent after treatment of Glu-GQDs than control, and the blebs and pore were observed after treatment of Gr-GQDs (Fig. 5(E) and (F)). Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) images support the results of AFM images (Fig. S3). A quantitative analysis of the cellular response (Fig. 6
                        ) can describe the difference in the cellular response upon treatment with the two GQD samples. The variables were statistically evaluated in each cell and each sample (p ≤ 0.05). In the case of NHDF cells, both Glu-GQDs and Gr-GQDs are statistically valid only at the average cell height and RMS roughness. The average cell height was increased to 4.78 μm, 4.48 from 3.07 after Glu-GQDs, Gr-GQDs treatment, respectively. The RMS cell roughness also was increased to 1297.83 nm, 1065.21 nm after Glu-GQDs, Gr-GQDs treatment, respectively. On the other hand, with HeLa cells, only the Gr-GQDs were statistically significant at the average cell height, and RMS roughness, cell stiffness. The average cell height was reduced to 2.82 from 4.06 after Gr-GQDs treatment as compared to control group. The RMS roughness of cell surface was reduced to 511.53 nm from 1008.67 nm after Gr-GQDs treatment. Furthermore, the cell stiffness (Young’s modulus) was reduced to 30.6 kPa from 40.93 kPa after Gr-GQDs treatment. The detailed values are given in Table S3. From these results, we can infer that in NHDF cells, both GQDs accumulate at the cell surface and pass through the cell membrane, and no mechanical tension/stress is produced in the cytoplasm, which indicates that a reorganization of the cytoskeleton does not occur. On the other hand, in HeLa cells, Glu-GQDs do not affect the cellular response significantly, whereas Gr-GQDs possibly translocate into the inner cell, leading to a reduction in the RMS roughness. Mechanical tension/stress is generated because of the reorganization of the cytoskeleton, which in turn is responsible for the reduced cell average height and stiffness.
